[49m[38;5;10m+      1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 8.6: Social Determinants of Health (SDOH) Extraction
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Medium-Complex · **Phase:** Production · **Estimated Cost:** ~$0.02-0.08 per note
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Here's a statistic that should bother anyone who works in healthcare: somewhere between 30% and 55% of health outcomes are driven by social and economic factors, not by clinical care. Housing instability, food insecurity, unemployment, social isolation, transportation barriers. These are the things that determine whether your patient can actually follow the care plan you just wrote. And yet, in most health systems, this information is trapped in unstructured text, invisible to the systems that coordinate care.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A social worker writes "Pt reports living in car for 3 weeks after eviction." A primary care physician notes "patient unable to afford medications, skipping doses." A nurse documents "no reliable transportation to dialysis appointments." A behavioral health intake form reads "client recently lost job, experiencing food insecurity."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This information exists. People are writing it down. But it's buried in progress notes, social work assessments, discharge summaries, and care coordination records. It's not coded. It's not structured. It doesn't feed into risk models. It doesn't trigger referrals. It doesn't show up in population health dashboards. And when a care manager opens that patient's chart six months later, they have to read through dozens of notes to find the sentence that says "this patient doesn't have a stable place to live."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The clinical consequences are real. A patient with uncontrolled diabetes who is food insecure needs a fundamentally different care plan than one who has stable housing and reliable meals. A heart failure patient without transportation to cardiology appointments will end up in the ED. A new mother experiencing domestic violence needs resources that have nothing to do with postpartum checkups. If your systems can't surface these factors, you're treating diseases in isolation from the lives your patients are actually living.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Payers care about this too. CMS has been pushing SDOH documentation through Z-codes (ICD-10-CM codes Z55-Z65), and value-based contracts increasingly include social risk adjustment. But Z-code capture rates are abysmal. Most clinicians don't code social factors even when they document them. The information is in the notes. It's just not in the structured data.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Extracting SDOH from clinical text is one of those problems where the concept sounds straightforward ("just find the sentences about housing") and the reality is genuinely hard. Let me explain why.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: Extracting Social Context from Clinical Language
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What Are Social Determinants of Health?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m SDOH is typically organized into five domains (following the Healthy People 2030 framework):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 1. **Economic Stability:** Employment, income, debt, food affordability, housing costs
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 2. **Education Access and Quality:** Literacy, language barriers, educational attainment
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 3. **Healthcare Access and Quality:** Insurance status, transportation to care, provider availability
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 4. **Neighborhood and Built Environment:** Housing quality, safety, environmental exposures, food deserts
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 5. **Social and Community Context:** Social isolation, incarceration history, domestic violence, discrimination
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Each domain contains dozens of specific factors. Housing alone includes: homelessness, housing instability, inadequate housing (lead paint, mold, overcrowding), housing cost burden, and temporary housing. And each of those can appear in text in hundreds of different ways.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why This Is Hard
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m SDOH extraction is harder than most clinical NLP tasks for a few specific reasons:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Sparse mentions.** In a typical clinical note, SDOH information might appear in one sentence out of fifty. The signal-to-noise ratio is terrible. A discharge summary that's 2,000 words might contain exactly one relevant sentence: "Patient reports difficulty affording medications." Compare this to medication extraction, where drug names appear on nearly every line of a medication reconciliation note.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Inconsistent language.** There's no standard vocabulary for documenting social factors. A physician writes "homeless." A social worker writes "experiencing homelessness." A nurse writes "lives in shelter." An intake form says "housing status: unstable." A progress note says "pt reports sleeping at different friends' houses." These all mean the same thing, but they look nothing alike to a pattern matcher.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Contextual interpretation required.** "Patient was referred to food pantry" is different from "patient reports food insecurity." The first implies a positive resource connection (problem being addressed). The second is an active unmet need. Your extraction system needs to distinguish between current risk, past risk that's been resolved, and risk that's being actively addressed. This is assertion classification territory (Recipe 8.8), and it matters because the downstream action is completely different for each.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Documenter variation.** Social workers write detailed social assessments with structured headings. Physicians mention SDOH as one-liners buried in a review of systems or assessment plan. Nurses document barriers to care in discharge instructions. Each discipline uses different conventions, different vocabularies, and embeds the information in different parts of the document. A single NLP model needs to handle all of them.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Sensitivity and bias.** SDOH data touches on poverty, race, substance use, domestic violence, and immigration status. Extracting this information and attaching it to patient records creates real ethical obligations. You need to think about who sees it, how it's used, and whether it could be weaponized (denied insurance, child protective services involvement, immigration enforcement). These aren't hypothetical concerns.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The NLP Techniques
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m SDOH extraction typically combines several NLP approaches:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Named Entity Recognition (NER):** Identify spans of text that mention SDOH-related concepts. "Living in car" is a housing-related entity. "Lost job last month" is an employment-related entity. Custom NER models trained on SDOH-annotated clinical text outperform general biomedical NER models because the entity types are social, not clinical.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Text Classification:** At the sentence or section level, classify text into SDOH domains. "Is this sentence about housing, food security, transportation, or something else?" Multi-label classification, because a single sentence can touch multiple domains ("patient lost job and was evicted" hits both economic stability and housing).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Negation and Assertion Detection:** Distinguish between present problems, absent problems, and resolved problems. "Patient denies food insecurity" is a negation. "Housing stable after shelter placement" is resolved. "Reports difficulty affording rent" is active. Getting this wrong means either missing real needs or creating false alerts.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Relation Extraction:** Connect the extracted SDOH mention to other entities. Who is experiencing the social need (the patient? a family member?)? What time frame (current? past?)? How severe (temporary setback vs. chronic condition)?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Rule-based Post-processing:** Pattern matching and lookup tables for common SDOH phrases that the ML model might miss. "S/H: homeless" in a social history section. "Undomiciled" as a single-word mention. "SDoH screen positive" in a screening tool note. Rules catch the formulaic patterns; ML catches the creative natural language.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The General Architecture Pattern
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The extraction pipeline looks like this at a conceptual level:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```text
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m [Clinical Notes] → [Section Detection] → [Sentence Scoring] → [Entity/Concept Extraction]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                                                         ↓
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m [Assertion Classification] → [SDOH Domain Mapping] → [Structured Output] → [Integration]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Section Detection:** Identify which part of the note you're reading. Social history sections and social work notes are high-yield. The assessment/plan section often contains one-liner SDOH mentions. Discharge instructions reference barriers. Section awareness helps you tune sensitivity: in a social history section, you can be more aggressive about extraction because the prior probability of SDOH content is higher.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Sentence Scoring:** Before running expensive entity extraction on every sentence in the note, run a fast binary classifier: "does this sentence contain SDOH-relevant content?" This filtering step keeps your pipeline efficient. Most sentences in a clinical note are clinically focused ("blood pressure 140/90, increased lisinopril to 20mg") and contain zero social information.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Entity/Concept Extraction:** For sentences that pass the filter, extract the specific SDOH concepts. This might be a span-based NER model ("experiencing [homelessness]_HOUSING") or a classification model that assigns SDOH categories to the entire sentence.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Assertion Classification:** Determine the status of each extracted concept. Present? Absent (denied/screened negative)? Historical? Being addressed? This step prevents false positives from negated mentions and distinguishes active needs from resolved ones.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **SDOH Domain Mapping:** Map the extracted concepts to a standardized SDOH taxonomy. Different organizations use different frameworks (Healthy People 2030, Gravity Project SDOH ontology, ICD-10 Z-codes, LOINC SDOH assessment codes). Your output should map to at least one standard to enable interoperability.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Integration:** Push structured SDOH data into downstream systems: problem lists, care management platforms, risk stratification models, referral engines, population health dashboards.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The AWS Implementation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why These Services
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Comprehend Medical for entity extraction.** Comprehend Medical is AWS's healthcare-specific NLP service. It extracts medical entities from clinical text, including some social determinants. Its `MEDICAL_CONDITION` and `TIME_EXPRESSION` entity types capture clinically relevant mentions, and you can use the detected entities as features. However, Comprehend Medical doesn't have a dedicated SDOH entity type, so we combine it with a custom classification layer for SDOH-specific extraction.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Comprehend (Custom Classification) for SDOH domain classification.** Train a custom multi-label text classifier on sentences labeled with SDOH domains. Comprehend's custom classification allows you to build models without managing infrastructure. You label training data, Comprehend trains and hosts the model, and you get an API endpoint.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon SageMaker for custom NER.** For SDOH-specific entity extraction beyond what Comprehend Medical provides, train a custom NER model on SageMaker. This handles the nuanced spans ("living in car," "skipping doses due to cost") that generic medical NER misses. SageMaker gives you full control over model architecture and training data.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Lambda for orchestration.** The extraction pipeline is a sequence of API calls (split text into sentences, classify, extract entities, apply assertions, map to taxonomy) that fits the stateless, event-driven Lambda model. Processing a single note takes 2-8 seconds depending on length.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon DynamoDB for extraction results.** Store structured SDOH findings per patient with efficient lookups by patient ID, encounter, or SDOH domain. Supports the downstream query patterns that care management platforms need.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon S3 for note storage and model artifacts.** Clinical notes arrive in S3 (from EHR data feeds), and extraction results archive there for compliance and reprocessing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Architecture Diagram
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```mermaid
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m flowchart LR
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     A[Clinical Notes\nS3 Data Lake] -->|S3 Event / Batch| B[Lambda\nSDOH Orchestrator]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     B -->|Sentence Splitting\n& Filtering| C[Comprehend Custom\nSDOH Classifier]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     C -->|SDOH Sentences| B
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     B -->|Entity Extraction| D[SageMaker Endpoint\nSDOH NER]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     B -->|Medical Context| E[Comprehend Medical]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     D -->|SDOH Entities| B
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     E -->|Negation/Assertions| B
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     B -->|Structured Output| F[DynamoDB\nSDOH Findings]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     B -->|Raw Archive| G[S3\nExtraction Archive]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     F -->|API| H[Care Management\nPopulation Health]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style C fill:#ff9,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style D fill:#f9f,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style F fill:#9ff,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Services** | Amazon Comprehend (custom classifier), Amazon Comprehend Medical, Amazon SageMaker (inference endpoint), AWS Lambda, Amazon DynamoDB, Amazon S3 |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | `comprehend:ClassifyDocument`, `comprehend:DetectEntities` (custom endpoint), `comprehendmedical:DetectEntitiesV2`, `sagemaker:InvokeEndpoint`, `s3:GetObject`, `s3:PutObject`, `dynamodb:PutItem`, `dynamodb:Query` |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **BAA** | AWS BAA signed (required: clinical notes contain PHI; SDOH data itself is highly sensitive) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Encryption** | S3: SSE-KMS; DynamoDB: encryption at rest (default); SageMaker endpoint: KMS encrypted; all API calls over TLS; Lambda CloudWatch Logs: KMS encryption configured |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **VPC** | Production: Lambda in VPC with VPC endpoints for S3, DynamoDB, SageMaker Runtime, Comprehend, Comprehend Medical, and CloudWatch Logs |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **CloudTrail** | Enabled: log all Comprehend, SageMaker, and S3 API calls for HIPAA audit |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Training Data** | SDOH-annotated clinical notes. The MIMIC-III/IV dataset has been used in research. The Social Work Assessment corpus or de-identified notes from your own system are ideal. Gravity Project reference materials for taxonomy alignment. Never use real PHI in model development without IRB approval and proper de-identification. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | Comprehend Custom Classification: ~$0.0005/unit (100 chars). Comprehend Medical: ~$0.01 per unit (100 chars). SageMaker real-time endpoint: ~$0.05-0.10/hour (ml.m5.large). Lambda + DynamoDB negligible. Per-note cost varies by length: ~$0.02-0.08 for a typical 500-2000 word note. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |------------|------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon Comprehend (Custom)** | Multi-label sentence classifier for SDOH domain detection |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon Comprehend Medical** | Medical entity extraction and negation/assertion detection |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon SageMaker** | Custom NER model endpoint for SDOH-specific entity spans |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Lambda** | Pipeline orchestration: split, classify, extract, assemble |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon DynamoDB** | Structured SDOH findings store with patient-level queries |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon S3** | Note ingestion, model artifacts, extraction archive |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Encryption key management for all data at rest |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon CloudWatch** | Metrics, logs, alarms for extraction quality monitoring |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 1: Note ingestion and section detection.** Clinical notes arrive in S3 from EHR data feeds (HL7 FHIR DocumentReference, CDA documents, or flat text exports). The first processing step identifies the note type and splits it into logical sections. Social history sections, social work assessments, and care coordination notes are high-priority for SDOH content. The assessment/plan and discharge instructions sections are secondary targets. Purely clinical sections (lab results, vital signs) can be skipped entirely to save processing cost. Skip this step and you waste compute on sections that will never contain SDOH information, and you lose the contextual signal that section headers provide.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION ingest_and_section(bucket, key):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Retrieve the clinical note from storage
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     note_text = read object from S3 at bucket/key
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Parse metadata: patient ID, encounter ID, note type, author role
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     metadata = extract_metadata(note_text)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Split into sections using header patterns
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Clinical notes use predictable section headers:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // "SOCIAL HISTORY:", "HPI:", "ASSESSMENT/PLAN:", etc.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     sections = split_by_section_headers(note_text)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Tag each section with SDOH relevance priority
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // High: Social History, Social Work Assessment, Barriers to Care
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Medium: Assessment/Plan, Discharge Instructions, Care Coordination
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Low/Skip: Lab Results, Vital Signs, Medications, Imaging
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each section in sections:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         section.priority = assign_sdoh_priority(section.header)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Return sections ordered by priority (high first)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // This lets us stop early if processing budget is constrained
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN metadata, sections sorted by priority descending
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 2: Sentence-level SDOH classification.** For each high-priority section, split into sentences and run each through the custom SDOH classifier. This is the filtering step that identifies which sentences contain SDOH-relevant content. The classifier is a multi-label model trained on sentences annotated with SDOH domains (housing, food, employment, transportation, social support, safety, education, financial). Most sentences will score below threshold and get discarded. A typical social history section of 10 sentences might yield 3-5 SDOH-relevant ones. A progress note might yield 0-1. This step is critical for precision: without it, downstream extraction runs on every sentence and produces a flood of false positives from clinically focused text that mentions social concepts tangentially.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m SDOH_DOMAINS = [
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "housing_instability",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "food_insecurity",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "transportation_barriers",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "financial_strain",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "employment_issues",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "social_isolation",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "interpersonal_violence",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "education_barriers",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "legal_issues",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "utility_difficulties"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m CLASSIFICATION_THRESHOLD = 0.60  // minimum confidence to consider a sentence SDOH-relevant
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION classify_sentences(sections):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     sdoh_candidates = empty list
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each section in sections WHERE section.priority >= MEDIUM:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         sentences = split_into_sentences(section.text)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FOR each sentence in sentences:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Call the custom Comprehend classifier endpoint
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    208[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Returns a list of SDOH domain labels with confidence scores
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             result = call Comprehend.ClassifyDocument with:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    210[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 text     = sentence
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    211[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 endpoint = SDOH_CLASSIFIER_ENDPOINT_ARN
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    212[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    213[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Keep sentences where at least one SDOH domain scores above threshold
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    214[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             relevant_labels = filter result.Labels WHERE score >= CLASSIFICATION_THRESHOLD
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    215[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    216[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             IF relevant_labels is not empty:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    217[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 append to sdoh_candidates: {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    218[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     sentence:       sentence,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    219[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     section_header: section.header,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    220[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     domains:        relevant_labels,   // which SDOH domains were detected
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    221[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     top_score:      max score from relevant_labels
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    222[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    223[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    224[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN sdoh_candidates
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    225[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    226[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    227[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 3: SDOH entity extraction.** For sentences that passed the classifier filter, extract specific SDOH entity spans using the custom NER model hosted on SageMaker. The NER model identifies the exact text spans that describe social needs: "living in car," "unable to afford medications," "no transportation to appointments." Entity types include SDOH_FACTOR (the social determinant itself), SEVERITY (acute, chronic, mild), TIMEFRAME (current, past, 3 weeks), and RESOURCE (food pantry, shelter, Medicaid). This granularity matters because "patient was homeless 5 years ago" and "patient is currently homeless" require completely different care management responses.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    228[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    229[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    230[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION extract_sdoh_entities(sdoh_candidates):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    231[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     findings = empty list
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    232[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    233[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each candidate in sdoh_candidates:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    234[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Call the custom SageMaker NER endpoint
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    235[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Input: sentence text
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    236[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Output: list of entity spans with types, offsets, and confidence
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    237[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ner_result = call SageMaker.InvokeEndpoint with:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    238[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             endpoint = SDOH_NER_ENDPOINT_NAME
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    239[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             body     = { "text": candidate.sentence }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    240[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    241[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Parse the NER response into structured entities
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    242[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         entities = parse_ner_response(ner_result)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    243[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    244[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FOR each entity in entities:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    245[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             append to findings: {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    246[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 text:           entity.text,           // "living in car"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    247[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 entity_type:    entity.type,           // SDOH_FACTOR, SEVERITY, TIMEFRAME, RESOURCE
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    248[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 sdoh_domains:   candidate.domains,     // from classifier: ["housing_instability"]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    249[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 confidence:     entity.confidence,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    250[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 source_sentence: candidate.sentence,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    251[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 section:        candidate.section_header,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    252[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 offsets:        entity.start, entity.end
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    253[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    254[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    255[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN findings
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    256[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    257[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    258[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 4: Assertion and negation detection.** Not every SDOH mention represents an active need. "Patient denies food insecurity" is a negative finding. "Housing stable after shelter placement" indicates a resolved issue. "If patient loses job, may need assistance" is hypothetical. This step uses Amazon Comprehend Medical's assertion detection to classify each finding as POSITIVE (active need), NEGATIVE (denied/screened negative), CONDITIONAL (hypothetical), or RESOLVED (previously present, now addressed). Comprehend Medical's `Trait` field includes `NEGATION` detection, and we supplement with rule-based patterns for SDOH-specific assertion language. Skip this step and you'll flood care managers with false alerts from negated screenings and resolved historical needs.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    259[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    260[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    261[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ASSERTION_PATTERNS = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    262[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "NEGATIVE": ["denies", "no evidence of", "screened negative", "not experiencing",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    263[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                  "does not report", "stable", "adequate", "sufficient"],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    264[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "RESOLVED": ["resolved", "connected to", "receiving services", "placed in",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    265[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                  "obtained housing", "enrolled in", "no longer"],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    266[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "CONDITIONAL": ["if", "may need", "at risk for", "should consider", "potential"]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    267[0m:[38;5;10m[49m }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    268[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    269[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION classify_assertions(findings, original_sentences):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    270[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each finding in findings:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    271[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // First pass: use Comprehend Medical for negation detection
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    272[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         cm_result = call ComprehendMedical.DetectEntitiesV2 with:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    273[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             text = finding.source_sentence
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    274[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    275[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Check if Comprehend Medical detected negation traits
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    276[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // on entities overlapping with our SDOH finding
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    277[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         has_negation = check_negation_traits(cm_result, finding.offsets)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    278[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    279[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF has_negation:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    280[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             finding.assertion = "NEGATIVE"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    281[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ELSE:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    282[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Second pass: rule-based assertion patterns for SDOH context
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    283[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             finding.assertion = match_assertion_patterns(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    284[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 finding.source_sentence,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    285[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 finding.text,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    286[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 ASSERTION_PATTERNS
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    287[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    288[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Default to POSITIVE if no negation/resolution pattern matched
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    289[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             IF finding.assertion is NULL:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    290[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 finding.assertion = "POSITIVE"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    291[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    292[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN findings
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    293[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    294[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    295[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 5: Taxonomy mapping and Z-code suggestion.** Map each positive finding to standardized terminologies. The Gravity Project SDOH Clinical Care ontology provides a structured vocabulary. ICD-10-CM Z-codes (Z55-Z65) provide billable diagnosis codes. LOINC provides assessment instrument codes. This mapping enables interoperability: downstream systems that understand SNOMED, ICD-10, or Gravity Project codes can consume the findings without parsing free text. It also supports the growing regulatory push for SDOH Z-code capture. The mapping table is a curated crosswalk between your internal SDOH domain labels and the relevant standard codes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    296[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    297[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```json
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    298[0m:[38;5;10m[49m {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    299[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "housing_instability": {
